xtremists seeking union with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. In 1983, the 150,000 Turkish Cypriots proclaimed their own breakaway state, which has been recognized only by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. A 2,300-man <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force patrols a dividing line splitting the island east to west. Efforts at reunification through a U.N.-sponsored federation plan have been deadlocked for more than two years. <PERSON> Kyprianou </PERSON>'s main plank was the rejection of any resumption of negotiations with the Turkish side unless the 35,000 Turkish troops and 65,000 settlers from mainland <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> withdraw from northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. His two main rivals also supported the withdrawal demand but did not make this a precondition for negotiations.
