<HEAD>Soviet Verification Procedures Insufficient for Arms Talks, U.S.
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has told the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that verification procedures worked out for medium-range missiles will not suffice for the strategic arms talks that begin again this week, senior arms control adviser <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> said Monday. `` We are calling for tough measures which will assure that we can verify Soviet compliance,'' <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The text of the speech was released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The Soviets, he said, can expedite progress on strategic arms reductions by abandoning their effort to link the reductions to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s pursuit of Star Wars technology. <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> accused the Soviets of delaying tactics, which he said are jeopardizing reaching an agreement on strategic arms in time for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s meeting with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in late spring or early summer. `` They appear to believe delaying tactics will reward them with a START treaty imbalanced in their favor,'' <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> said. `` I hope they will recognize that their intransigence is only dimming hopes for an agreement before the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit meeting.'' Even with the tough verification procedures approved two months ago as part of the treaty banning medium-range missile, <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> said, `` it would be misleading to suggest we are on a roll toward a START agreement.'' `` We are concerned that the Soviets' heavy reliance on very large ICBMs may give them a sense of confidence that they could gain a critical advantage by striking first,'' <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> said. By seeking a limit that permanently reduces both the number and the proportion of intercontinental ballistic missiles in the Soviet armory, he said, `` we are asking the Soviets in effect to renounce any motion that nuclear war is winnable, even if initiated pre-emptively.''
