<HEAD>Labor Federation Says Job Safety Laws `Out of Date'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AFL-CIO-Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to give government inspectors the power to close unsafe workplaces and make it easier to file criminal complaints for violations resulting in death or injury. Holding its annual winter meeting here this week, the labor federation's 36-member executive council said the 17-year-old Occupational Health and Safety Act is `` badly out of date'' with other job and community safety laws. `` Reforms are needed to expand protections to workers not currently covered, to expedite standard setting and to require working training and education,'' the council said. Although the details of the requested legislation have yet to be worked out, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Seminario </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s occupational safety and health department, said it will include a provision broadening coverage to several groups of workers now exempted Among them are workers in the nuclear industry, some 3 million transportation workers and more than 14 million employees of state and local governments. The 14.3-million-member labor federation said it also wants to give inspectors for the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> the same authority that a sister agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, has to shut down a plant or other workplace when there is a significant hazard posing an immediate threat to workers. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors can do that in some limited cases now, but they first have to obtain a court order. Some companies also have refused to allow <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGA